Kern 2.0
========

A hobby x86 kernel written in C and x86 assembly, built from scratch without
any standard library. Boots via GRUB (Multiboot), runs in 32-bit protected
mode, and provides an interactive shell over PS/2 keyboard input.


Build Requirements
------------------

  - i686-elf-gcc     (cross-compiler targeting bare-metal x86)
  - i686-elf-ld      (cross-linker)
  - GRUB             (grub-mkrescue)
  - xorriso          (ISO generation)
  - QEMU (optional)  (qemu-system-i386, for running locally)


Building and Running
--------------------

  make              Build the kernel and produce kern.iso
  make run          Build and launch in QEMU
  make run-headless Launch in QEMU with output redirected to stdio
  make clean        Remove all build artefacts


Project Structure
-----------------

  boot/             Multiboot-compliant assembly entry point and stack setup
  kernel/           Kernel main, printf, and shell
  cpu/              GDT, IDT, ISR stubs, PIC driver, and I/O port helpers
  drivers/          VGA text-mode driver, PS/2 keyboard driver, PIT timer


Kernel Subsystems
-----------------

GDT (Global Descriptor Table)
  Sets up three segments: null, kernel code (ring 0), and kernel data (ring 0),
  each covering the full 4 GB address space in 32-bit protected mode. Loaded
  via a far jump to flush the CPU pipeline and reload all segment registers.

IDT + PIC (Interrupt Descriptor Table / Programmable Interrupt Controller)
  The 8259 PIC is remapped so hardware IRQs 0-15 land on vectors 0x20-0x2F,
  avoiding collision with the CPU's reserved exception vectors (0-31). The IDT
  is populated with 32 exception gates and 16 hardware IRQ gates, each backed
  by an assembly stub that saves CPU state, calls a C dispatch function, sends
  EOI, and returns via iret. Per-vector handlers can be registered at runtime.

PS/2 Keyboard (IRQ 1)
  Reads scan code set 1 from I/O port 0x60 on each IRQ 1 fire. Translated
  characters are placed in a 256-byte circular buffer. The shell reads from
  this buffer via a blocking call that halts the CPU until a key arrives.

PIT Timer (IRQ 0)
  Programs channel 0 of the 8253/8254 PIT to fire at 1000 Hz (one tick per
  millisecond). A volatile tick counter is incremented on each IRQ, providing
  a monotonic millisecond clock via timer_get_ticks().

VGA Text Driver
  Writes directly to the VGA framebuffer at 0xB8000 (80x25 characters). Handles
  newlines, horizontal scrolling, screen scroll, and backspace cursor movement.

kprintf
  A minimal kernel printf supporting %c, %s, %d, %u, %x, and %X. Implemented
  with stdarg.h (available in freestanding GCC) and no heap dependency.

Shell
  A simple interactive command interpreter. Displays a prompt, reads a line
  with backspace editing, parses the first word as a command name, and
  dispatches to the matching handler.


Shell Commands
--------------

  help              List available commands
  clear             Clear the screen
  echo <text>       Print text to the screen
  ticks             Show milliseconds elapsed since boot
  halt              Disable interrupts and halt the CPU


Planned / Next Steps
--------------------

  - Physical memory manager (parse Multiboot memory map, bitmap allocator)
  - Virtual memory and paging (page directory / page table setup)
  - Heap allocator (kmalloc / kfree)
  - User mode and system calls
